    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1943-12-11T04:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1943-12-11T04:00:00-05:00" n="532"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d532">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.24/1677: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Harriman</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Moscow</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1943-12-11T12:00:00+03:00"
                            >December 11, 1943—noon</date>.<lb/>[Received December 12—10:02
                        a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>2194. I have been keeping in touch with Soviet Commissar for Foreign Trade and
                    with Chinese Ambassador here on shipment of Lend-Lease supplies for China by the
                    Turk-Sib Railroad and overland route. Reference Department’s 938, October 1, 10
                        p.m.,<note n="36" xml:id="d532fn36">See footnote 35, <ref target="#pg_612"
                            >p. 612</ref>.</note> had thought matter was progressing favorably. On
                    December 10 Counselor of Chinese Embassy told Hamilton<note n="37"
                        xml:id="d532fn37">Maxwell M. Hamilton, Counselor of Embassy in the Soviet
                        Union.</note> in response to inquiry that about 2 weeks ago the Chinese
                    Ambassador had communicated to Chinese Foreign Office Soviet stipulation that
                    Chinese Government supply to Soviet Union 1300 tons of commodities per month
                    independent of supplies China had agreed to supply under other arrangements;
                    also Soviet request for list commodities to be conveyed into China in order that
                    computation of charges might be made. Counselor said that Chinese Ambassador had
                    as yet received no reply from Foreign Office. He expressed opinion Chinese
                    Government would find difficulty meeting stipulation regarding supplying of 1300
                    tons of new supplies.</p>
                <p>Repeated to Chungking.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Harriman</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
